result.execSummary:
The defendant Jamie L. Preder was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

[MK] case called at 1:55pm. 
Defendant Jamie L. Preder in court with Attorney Steven Luchsinger.  DA Susan Happ appears for the State of Wisconsin.  
Maximum penalties recited; Constitutional rights reviewed; plea of " No Contest " entered on Count #1; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance verified; the Court accepts the plea, finds the Defendant guilty, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.
Domestic Abuse finding is made. 

On Motion of the State, the Court reads-in and dismisses Count #2.

On Count #1, the Court withholds sentence, and places Ms. Preder on Probation for one year, with conditions:
--to undergo assessment, treatment, or counseling as required by the Agent
--no possession of any dangerous weapons
--no acts or threats of violence
--to complete Certified Batterers Intervention Programming 
--to comply with DNA sample provision upon demand
--to pay costs, fees, assessments and surcharges, including the Domestic Abuse surcharge and the DNA surcharge  
--to reimburse Jefferson County for court-appointed attorney fees 


Days credit for time already served:  1 day
Upon successful completion of this Probation Term, the Court authorizes expungement of this case under Statute 973.015.
recess 2:04pm.

[MK] case called at 3:09pm. 
Defendant Jamie L. Preder in court.  ADA Theresa A Beck appears for the State of Wisconsin.
In response to the Court's inquiries about her efforts to seek counsel, Ms. Preder indicates that she tried calling Jayme McCoy and that she contacted the Clerk of Court's Office but they told her that she was supposed to get an attorney.  Ms. Preder indicates that she has not had time to contact the Public Defenders Office-- she is working, she is making efforts to have placement of her young daughter, and she is sleeping. 
The Court finds that by failing to act to make efforts to seek counsel, Ms. Preder has waived that right.  
The Court reviews the process for applying for PD representation.  If Ms. Preder finds that she does not qualify for PD representation she may petition for the appointment of counsel.  
The maximum penalties are recited. 
The Court schedules the case for Jury Trial. The Court emphasizes to Ms. Preder that she should contact the PD Office yet this month if she wishes to apply for representation; she cannot apply shortly before the trial date is approaching and expect an attorney to be prepared to proceed. 
The Court indicates that the Bond and conditions of release remain in effect.
